•	In Nmap, the flags -sS, -sN, -sF, -sX, and -sA are different scan techniques used to detect open, closed, or filtered ports. Each one behaves differently and is useful in different situations — especially when trying to bypass firewalls or IDS (Intrusion Detection Systems).

1️⃣ TCP SYN Scan (Stealth Scan)
Scan name: SYN Scan
Command: nmap -sS <IP>
Packet sent: ➡️ SYN
Response: Open: SYN-ACK ✅
                Closed: RST ❌
Explanation:Nmap sends a SYN packet. If SYN-ACK is received, the port is open. Nmap does not complete the handshake (stealthy).

2️⃣ TCP Connect Scan
Scan name: Connect Scan
Command: nmap -sT <IP>
Packet sent: ➡️ SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK
Response: Open: Full TCP handshake completed
           Closed: RST
Explanation: Uses OS TCP stack and completes the 3-way handshake. Noisy but reliable.

3️⃣ TCP ACK Scan
Scan name: ACK Scan
Command: nmap -sA <IP>
Packet sent:➡️ ACK
Response:Unfiltered: RST
         Filtered: No response / ICMP error
Explanation: Used to detect firewall rules, not open ports.

4️⃣ TCP FIN Scan
Scan name: FIN Scan
Command:nmap -sF <IP>
Packet sent: ➡️ FIN
Response: Open: No response
                Closed: RST
Explanation: Relies on RFC behavior. Open ports ignore FIN packets.

5️⃣ TCP NULL Scan

Scan name: NULL Scan
Command: nmap -sN <IP>
Packet sent: ➡️ No flags set (NULL)
Response: Open: No response
               Closed: RST
Explanation: Packet has no flags. Some systems mishandle it → useful for evasion.

6️⃣ TCP Xmas Scan

Scan name: Xmas Scan
Command: nmap -sX <IP>
Packet sent: ➡️ FIN + PSH + URG 🎄
Response: Open: No response
          Closed: RST
Explanation: Flags light up like a Christmas tree. Same logic as FIN/NULL scans.
